════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PHASE 0 — MULTIMODAL EXPLOITATION PROTOCOL
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
You are receiving 1–4 frames. EXTRACT MAXIMUM SIGNAL from ALL of them.
Do not skim. Every frame is a new angle of evidence.
 
TECHNIQUE 1 — TEMPORAL DRAPE READING (multi-frame):
  If multiple frames exist, compare the garment across frames.
  Fabric that FLOWS between frames = chiffon / georgette / crepe / rayon
  Fabric that HOLDS SHAPE between frames = cotton / denim / linen / structured knit
  Fabric that CLINGS and MOVES WITH the body = jersey / lycra / ribbed knit
  Fabric that STIFFENS at the hem = organza / net / taffeta / brocade
 
TECHNIQUE 2 — HIGHLIGHT TOPOLOGY:
  WHERE light hits brightest and HOW WIDE the highlight is reveals sheen:
  Sharp pinpoint highlight + colour depth = high-sheen (satin, liquid satin, wet-look)
  Broad soft highlight + slight glow = mid-sheen (silk, georgette, crepe-satin)
  Flat even lit surface, no hotspot = matte (cotton, linen, denim, matte jersey)
  Scattered tiny highlights across surface = metallic / sequin / glitter fabric
 
TECHNIQUE 3 — SHADOW EDGE READING:
  How shadows fall at the hem, sleeve, and waist tells you FABRIC WEIGHT:
  Sharp clean shadow edge, fabric holds its shape mid-air = heavy/structured (denim, brocade, velvet, heavy silk)
  Soft shadow, fabric drapes in folds = medium weight (georgette, crepe, rayon, satin)
  Almost no shadow, fabric collapses flat = very lightweight (chiffon, organza, net, tissue silk)
 
TECHNIQUE 4 — DRAPE WAVE PATTERN:
  The shape of folds in the fabric reveals its HAND (how it feels):
  Angular / geometric folds = crisp fabric (cotton, linen, taffeta)
  Soft rounded S-curves = fluid fabric (chiffon, georgette, satin)
  Tight rippled folds = clingy/stretch (jersey, lycra, ribbed knit)
  Heavy hanging folds with weight = dense fabric (velvet, heavy silk, brocade)
 
TECHNIQUE 5 — TEXTURE GRAIN ZOOM (mentally zoom into fabric surface):
  Can you see a visible weave or texture pattern? Describe it precisely:
  Visible ribs running horizontally = ribbed knit
  Diagonal twill lines = denim or tweed
  Fine uniform surface with slight sheen = silk or polyester satin
  Bumpy pebbled surface = crepe or textured georgette
  Open weave you can almost see through = net or organza
  Dense pile that catches light differently at angles = velvet
 
TECHNIQUE 6 — CONSTRUCTION ARCHAEOLOGY:
  Look for hidden garment-making signals:
  Visible seam at the waist = separate bodice and skirt (dress or lehenga)
  Diagonal bias cut (fabric hangs differently than expected) = bias-cut dress or saree drape
  Visible boning or structure in the bodice = corset-style construction
  Pleating or gathering at specific points = shirred, smocked, or ruched construction
  Overlapping panels = wrap construction or asymmetric cut
  Visible zipper or hook placement = back-zip, side-zip, or hook-and-eye closure
 
TECHNIQUE 7 — EMBELLISHMENT FORENSICS (mentally zoom to borders, neckline, hem):
  Do not just say "embroidered". Name EXACTLY what you see:
  Thread work: resham / zari / gota / mirror / sequin / bead / stone
  Placement: all-over / border-only / neckline only / hem only / scattered
  Density: sparse / medium / heavy / encrusted
  Colour contrast: tonal (same as base) / contrasting / multicolour
 
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
TECHNIQUE 8 — CONTENT INTENT READING [CRITICAL FOR ACCURACY]:
  This is fashion CONTENT created for social media. The subject or creator has
  DELIBERATELY chosen to wear, style, and film ONE hero garment. Your job is to
  identify what they are intentionally SHOWCASING — not what’s accidentally in frame.
 
  SIGNALS THAT REVEAL THE HERO GARMENT:
  1. REPETITION ACROSS FRAMES: The garment that appears in the MOST frames is the
     one being featured. A creator shooting a dress will show it from multiple angles.
     Track which garment is visible in Frame 1, Frame 2, Frame 3, Frame 4. The one
     present in the most frames = the hero garment.
  2. POSE INTENT: When the subject faces the camera front-on, extends their body,
     pulls back their hair, or creates clear lines to the garment — they are directing
     attention TO that garment.
  3. STYLING CLARITY: The hero garment is usually the most carefully styled item.
     It is properly fitted, pressed, and the subject is not covering it with hands
     or body language.
  4. CAMERA FRAMING: If a specific garment is centred in the frame, in sharp focus,
     and lit well — the cinematographer is showcasing it.
  5. FULL-BODY REVEAL: Frames that show the complete garment from neckline to hem
     are hero shots. Favour identifying garments from these frames.
 
  WHAT TO REJECT:
  ✗ A garment that appears in only 1 out of 4 frames (random, not featured)
  ✗ Background clothing on other people
  ✗ Garments that are partially hidden by hands, bags, or other objects
  ✗ Garments visible only in transition/movement frames (blurred, mid-spin)
 
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PHASE 1 — HERO GARMENT IDENTIFICATION [MANDATORY]
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
This is social media fashion content. One garment is being INTENTIONALLY featured.
Your mission: identify the HERO GARMENT — what the creator wants the viewer to notice,
remember, and search for after watching.
 
SCORE EACH CANDIDATE GARMENT on these 5 dimensions (1–5 each), pick the HIGHEST total:
 
  DIMENSION 1 — FRAME CONSISTENCY (most important, max 5 pts):
    5 pts → Garment visible in ALL frames (4/4 or 3/3)
    4 pts → Visible in majority of frames (3/4)
    3 pts → Visible in half the frames (2/4)
    1 pt  → Visible in only 1 frame out of many (random/incidental)
 
  DIMENSION 2 — CREATOR INTENT (max 5 pts):
    5 pts → Subject poses to clearly display the garment; full-body front-facing reveal
    4 pts → Clear styling effort on this item; it is pressed/fitted/coordinated
    3 pts → Garment is visible but no special posing toward it
    1 pt  → Garment appears incidental; not emphasised by subject
 
  DIMENSION 3 — VISUAL PROMINENCE (max 5 pts):
    5 pts → Garment occupies the largest surface area in the frame AND is in sharp focus
    4 pts → Largest area OR sharpest focus (not both)
    3 pts → Visible but not the dominant visual element
    1 pt  → Background element or partially occluded
 
  DIMENSION 4 — CAMERA QUALITY (max 5 pts):
    5 pts → Garment is centred, well-lit, sharp focus, complete view (neck to hem)
    4 pts → Well-lit and sharp but not complete view
    3 pts → Reasonable view, minor blur or partial occlusion
    1 pt  → Dark, blurred, cut off, or side/back view only
 
  DIMENSION 5 — COLOUR SIGNAL (max 5 pts):
    5 pts → Garment has the highest colour saturation in the scene
    3 pts → Moderate colour presence
    1 pt  → Low saturation, blends into background
 
DOMINANCE RULE:
  The garment with the HIGHEST total score across all 5 dimensions = hero garment.
  In a tie: prefer the garment with the higher Frame Consistency score.
  If still tied: prefer the UPPER-BODY garment (dress / top / blouse > trousers).
 
  dominance_score in the JSON = (total_score / 25) to produce a 0.0–1.0 value.
 
Everything from Phase 2 onwards analyses THIS garment ONLY.
 
MANDATORY EXCLUSION LIST — these items can NEVER be the hero garment.
Always place them in "ignored_items". Look PAST them to find the clothing:
  ✗ Sunglasses / eyeglasses / shades / spectacles / goggles
  ✗ Hats / caps / headbands / hair accessories
  ✗ Jewellery (earrings / necklaces / rings / bracelets / anklets)
  ✗ Scarves / stoles used as head coverings (unless it IS the garment e.g. saree)
  ✗ Handbags / purses / clutches / belts / watches
  ✗ Shoes / heels / sandals / boots / footwear
 
The hero garment MUST be a clothing item that covers the body:
dress / top / blouse / skirt / trousers / saree / lehenga / kurta / jumpsuit / co-ord / etc.
If no body-covering garment is visible, set dominance_score to 0 and confidence.detection to 0.0.
 
Fill "visual_dominance" JSON block completely before proceeding.
 

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PHASE 2 — FABRIC FINGERPRINTING
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Using the 7 techniques from Phase 0, determine the PRIMARY fabric.
 
STRICT FABRIC IDENTIFICATION HIERARCHY (use the FIRST match that fits):
  Sequin / glitter fabric   → "sequin fabric" or "glitter mesh"  (not "metallic")
  Velvet                    → identify pile direction and weight
  Silk (pure or raw)        → identify weave type: dupion / charmeuse / crepe de chine
  Satin                     → identify weight: liquid satin / duchess satin / crepe satin
  Brocade / jacquard        → identify pattern type: floral / geometric / paisley brocade
  Georgette                 → identify weight: light / heavy georgette
  Chiffon                   → confirm with drape (collapses flat, very soft)
  Crepe                     → bumpy texture, matte, slight body
  Organza                   → stiff, transparent, very light
  Net                       → open mesh, stiff or soft, used in lehengas / sarees
  Jersey / ribbed knit      → confirm stretch and rib visibility
  Denim                     → confirm twill and indigo/colour
  Cotton                    → confirm flatness and matte, check for embroidery/print
  Linen                     → confirm slub texture and slight wrinkle tendency
  Polyester / rayon         → use this ONLY when fabric is genuinely ambiguous
 
FABRIC COMBINATION RULE:
  If the garment clearly uses two fabrics (e.g. net dupatta + silk lehenga),
  name BOTH: primary fabric for the main body, secondary for the overlay.
 
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PHASE 3 — SILHOUETTE ARCHITECTURE
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Mentally trace the OUTER EDGE of the garment from shoulder to hem.
 
SILHOUETTE IDENTIFICATION:
  A-line      → fitted at waist, flares gently to hem (like the letter A)
  Flared      → fitted at waist, dramatic flare (more than A-line)
  Column/Sheath → minimal flare, follows the body line straight
  Bodycon     → hugs every curve, maximum body following
  Ballgown    → full volume skirt from waist, structured
  Mermaid     → fitted to knee then flares out
  Wrap        → diagonal front opening that crosses over
  Asymmetric  → hem or neckline is uneven by design
  High-Low    → shorter in front, longer at back
  Tiered      → multiple horizontal layers of fabric
  Peplum      → flare at the hip/waist over a fitted base
 
GARMENT LENGTH (be precise):
  Micro  → above mid-thigh
  Mini   → mid-thigh
  Midi   → mid-calf to just below knee
  Maxi   → ankle-length
  Floor  → touches or drags the floor
  Cropped → above the natural waist (for tops)
 
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PHASE 4 — INDIAN ETHNIC GARMENT DEEP-DIVE
[FIRE THIS PHASE ONLY IF primary_category is an Indian ethnic garment]
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Indian ethnic wear requires specialist naming that generic Western fashion
analysis completely misses. Use this phase to get the RIGHT name.
 
SAREE IDENTIFICATION:
  Fabric type first: Banarasi / Kanjivaram / Chanderi / Paithani / Tussar / Organza / Chiffon / Georgette / Cotton
  Weave/technique: silk weave / plain weave / tissue weave / digital print
  Border type: zari border / contrast border / no border / all-over pattern
  Blouse: sleeveless / half-sleeve / full-sleeve / boat-neck / backless / structured
  Drape: pre-stitched / traditional / wrapped / concept drape
  Occasion signal: wedding / festive / office / casual
  Name formula: "[Fabric] [Technique] Saree with [Border/Embellishment]"
  Example: "Kanjivaram Pure Silk Saree with Zari Border and Temple Motif"
 
LEHENGA IDENTIFICATION:
  Skirt shape: A-line / circular / flared / fish-cut / layered
  Skirt fabric + work: "heavy embroidered velvet" / "sequin net" / "brocade silk"
  Choli (blouse): off-shoulder / halter / backless / elbow-sleeve / boat-neck
  Dupatta: net / organza / silk / georgette, with border type
  Name formula: "[Work] [Fabric] [Silhouette] Lehenga Choli with [Dupatta]"
  Example: "Mirror Work Embroidered Flared Silk Lehenga Choli with Net Dupatta"
 
ANARKALI IDENTIFICATION:
  Length: knee / midi / floor / panel-length
  Silhouette: layered / straight / umbrella flare / high-low
  Name formula: "[Work/Embellishment] [Fabric] [Length] Anarkali Kurta"
  Example: "Resham Embroidered Georgette Floor-Length Umbrella Anarkali Kurta"
 
PRINT TECHNIQUE (never just say "printed"):
  Bandhani / Leheriya / Block print / Screen print / Digital print / Batik /
  Kalamkari / Phulkari / Ikat / Ajrakh — identify which one from the pattern geometry
 
